Tumor CAD - Model 1: Tumour Segmentation¶

-Aaron T

For my FYP topic, I proposed a 2-way model architecture that utilized semantic segmentation of a 3D MRI scan, into classifying the tumours by their grade accordingly. This IPython notebook contains the entire code-base necessary to execute the model, with the appropriate explanations along the way.
Remember that most of this code is the raw workbook itself, much of which I decided to keep for reference purposes, as it is important that someone who intends to understand how to replicate this work will know what can be skipped/kept, and how it reached the end-result.
For that reason, Red font indicates mandatory sections. You MUST run them at any time, or the code will not work. On the other hand, Blue font indicates optional. These are either experimentations, or side functions that don't really impact the final code. I still strongly recommend trying them for the sake of understanding how they work.

These are the general imports used for this project. The main contributors in this case that may need to be downloaded before running these are:

  • __SimpleITK__. Needed for the BiasFieldCorrection, but entirely optional
  • __Numpy/Matplotlib/Pandas/Pickle/Scipy__. No explanation needed
  • __Nibabel & Nilearn__. EXTREMELY IMPORTANT to get these one
  • __Medpy__. Optional, only needed for the first few sections, which can be viewed instantly without running anyways
  • __Keras__. Obviously needed for the model
  • tifffile/libtiff. This one is only if you intend to print out the results as .tiff files. This was done before, but generally I don't recommend it due to how much space it takes, so just view the results manually.

Analysis
As referenced in the thesis, the first step is to understand how the data looks like. We need to keep in mind that this is a time-series based data, so the image should be channels of 2D images. To view them, normally we can use existing libraries for that. However, I wanted to create a function that can perform it manually, and with a different filetype.
The function you see below only applies to .mha files. These are BRATS '16 and earlier version files. I worked with them initially before migrating over to Nifti in BRATS '17 and later. Nifti does not have as clean of a plotting function, so this is why I kept the .mha version. It basically plots the image from the z coordinate every N intervals, which is the counter variable.

Context¶

BRATS is the name of an annual MICCAI challenge known as the Brain Tumor Segmentation Challenge. This project was one of the submissions inside said challenge, inspired by the works from Imperial College and UCL. Brain MRI scans of Benign/Malignant patients are provided to contestants for creating a model around accurately diagnosing them. Note that these are several gigabytes large, so upload to Github is outright impossible.

In [2]:
def mha_plot(data, number):
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))
    columns = 5
    rows = 6
    counter = 0
    for i in range(1,columns*rows+1):
        if counter >=155:
            #counter==155
            break
        img = data[:,:,counter]
        fig.add_subplot(rows, columns, i)
        plt.gca().set_title(counter)
        plt.imshow(img, cmap=cm.Greys_r)
        counter += number
    plt.tight_layout()

An observation to be made here is how the slices do not appear in every slice. This patient's scan for example, doesn't have slices from 0-20, and 140-155 (varies). Having this means that fitting this image into the model raw would mean alot more slices/images for it to handle, which are also meaningless. Cutting them down would save time for training.

Here is where experimentation on artifact removal was done. The following processes were done:

  • Smoothing. This is done with the Nibabel/Nilearn techniques, and is elaborated more in the report.
  • Enhancement. Mainly a visual thing, the image scans can be quite dim, making it difficult to view the images. Changing the 'dim' variable to negative values increases contrast, and raising it decreases contrast.

Smoothing is important in trading off spatial features against noise. Here multiple plots were done with gradually increasing intensities of smoothing, to see which length is close enough without destroying the tumor details. Personal recommendations are 1-2mm, but 3mm is still okay.

Cropping
This section handles the resizing of the image as mentioned earlier. Given how some patient scans have backgrounds from 0-20, or sometimes 0-15, 0-10, they vary too much to use a bare average. What this function does (used from someone else) is that it passes a threshold through each slice, and if there is the presence of a foreground pixel, it is kept. Otherwise that slice is cut.
Then it performs it again on the edges of each image, into a bounding box. There is also a 1 pixel pad of background on each image, just for safety measures.

In [2]:
from nilearn.image.image import check_niimg
from nilearn.image.image import _crop_img_to as crop_img_to


def crop_img(img, rtol=1e-8, copy=True, return_slices=False):
    img = check_niimg(img)
    data = img.get_data()
    infinity_norm = max(-data.min(), data.max())
    passes_threshold = np.logical_or(data < -rtol * infinity_norm,
                                     data > rtol * infinity_norm)

    if data.ndim == 4:
        passes_threshold = np.any(passes_threshold, axis=-1)
    coords = np.array(np.where(passes_threshold))
    start = coords.min(axis=1)
    end = coords.max(axis=1) + 1

    # pad with one voxel to avoid resampling problems
    start = np.maximum(start - 1, 0)
    end = np.minimum(end + 1, data.shape[:3])

    slices = [slice(s, e) for s, e in zip(start, end)]

    if return_slices:
        return slices

    return crop_img_to(img, slices, copy=copy)

Examples
An example of the cropping on a NIFTI image was then done to see if the padding works, so no details are accidentally removed. There isn't an issue, fortunately. The size also drops considerably, from 240x240x155 to 66x97x97 in this case.

Downsampling
Downsampling is experimented with here, where the size is essentially cut in half from a 1x1x1 voxel to a 2x2x2 voxel. Every 8 pixels count as one now, which also severely generalizes the image.
Here is an interesting tidbit of information found while randomly experimenting with the methods. It turns out smoothing should be done before downsampling. The figures below are a good example of this, which is because smoothing it before allows for the tumor's main features (pay attention to the necrotic tissue in the tumor core) are preserved when smoothed, which will retain post resampling, rather than the other way around.

In [10]:
segpath = './data/CBICA_OT.nii.gz'
outsegpath = './data/CBICA_OT_edited.nii.gz'

before = nibabel.load(segpath)
smoothb4 = image.smooth_img(before, fwhm=2)
after = nibabel.processing.resample_to_output(before, [2,2,2])
smoothbefore = nibabel.processing.resample_to_output(smoothb4, [2,2,2])
smoothafter = image.smooth_img(after, fwhm=2)
print('resampling:',before.shape, after.shape)
print('smoothing:', smoothbefore.shape, smoothafter.shape)

plotting.plot_img(crop_img(before)) #Fresh input
plotting.plot_img(crop_img(after)) #Downsample only
plotting.plot_img(crop_img(smoothbefore)) #Smooth then downsample
plotting.plot_img(crop_img(smoothafter)) #Downsample then smooth

Affine Transformation/Bias Field Correction
This section was omitted entirely after some time. One of them was that the Nibabel libraries do not have bias field correction, but SimpleITK does. However:

  • SimpleITK's function takes an INSANELY long time, of around 7-10 minutes per FILE. 10 minutes 4 files 285 patients = 190 hours just to process
  • SimpleITK is also outdated/not really supported much since, and constantly runs into errors processing the SAME file at times
  • Nibabel doesn't have any package capable of doing these, and cannot run sitk files post function

Therefore, this section was abandoned. If you intend to give it a try on your own, use these functions, they work 60% of the time.

In [10]:
def make_affine(simpleITKImage):
    # get affine transform in LPS
    c = [simpleITKImage.TransformContinuousIndexToPhysicalPoint(p)
         for p in ((1, 0, 0),
                   (0, 1, 0),
                   (0, 0, 1),
                   (0, 0, 0))]
    c = np.array(c)
    affine = np.concatenate([
        np.concatenate([c[0:3] - c[3:], c[3:]], axis=0),
        [[0.], [0.], [0.], [1.]]
    ], axis=1)
    affine = np.transpose(affine)
    # convert to RAS to match nibabel
    affine = np.matmul(np.diag([-1., -1., 1., 1.]), affine)
    return affine

This is an instance where the N4 Bias Field Correction was ran. Sometimes this code doesn't work, so just rerun it again until it works (It breaks down for no reason sometimes, then fixes itself). Here you can see some dim edges on the brain are now lighted up with a more normal contrast across the brain. Shame it could not be properly implemented, as this would have been greatly beneficial in the model.

Image Labels
To fully understand how the segmentation would work, first we analyze the annotated segmentations provided by MICCAI. Here, we can see that at slice 78 (reference to above), there is a mixture of the array being in 0,1,2,4. These indicate the pixel classes that the model needs to identify: 1 for the core (barely visible here), 2 for the Edema, and 4 for the enhancing tumor. 0 would be the background, which is everything else not the ROI

In [57]:
from pprint import pprint
import numpy
def fullprint(*args, **kwargs):
    opt = numpy.get_printoptions()
    np.set_printoptions(threshold=numpy.inf)
    pprint(*args, **kwargs)
    numpy.set_printoptions(**opt)

beforedata = np.array(after.dataobj)
fullprint(beforedata[78])

This is purely a sanity check to make sure the segmentation aligns nicely with the original image. It does. Whilst visual and not necessary for the final work, there is an important aspect needed to be addressed here:

Masks are an additional image that is designed to be overlapped over another image (if X = mask, Y = image, X overlaps Y) to highlight the overlapping regions, or everything else. This is the way we detect an anomaly/object in any picture, or in this case: the tumor. The GT (Ground Truth) mask overlays the T1 contrast MRI to give the highlighted tumor region shown in the bottom left picture.

Dataset Formation
Here the training set and validation set are made, with the self-created labels depending on their HGG/LGG status. HGG = Malignant = 0 LGG = Benign = 1 Similiar to the binary classifiers normally seen in "Dogs vs Cats" CNN, but on a 3D image, and requiring specific features distinguished.

In [3]:
HGG_dir_list = next(os.walk('./BRATS18_Training/HGG/'))[1]
# print(len(HGG_dir_list))
LGG_dir_list = next(os.walk('./BRATS18_Training/LGG/'))[1]
# print(len(LGG_dir_list))
valid_list = next(os.walk('./BRATS18_Validation/'))[1]

tumor_type_dict = {}

for patientID in HGG_dir_list+LGG_dir_list:
    #print(patientID)
    if patientID in HGG_dir_list:
        #tumor_type_dict[patientID] = "HGG"
        tumor_type_dict[patientID] = 0
    elif patientID in LGG_dir_list:
        #tumor_type_dict[patientID] = "LGG"
        tumor_type_dict[patientID] = 1

print('count:',len(tumor_type_dict), '|| HGG:',len(HGG_dir_list), '|| LGG:', len(LGG_dir_list))
for patientID in HGG_dir_list+LGG_dir_list:
    print(patientID, ':',tumor_type_dict[patientID])
print('\n================\n')
print('count:',len(valid_list))
for patientID in valid_list:
    print(patientID)

Bias Correction ~ Scrapped
The attempted N4 Bias correction method attempted to be done on all files. Took too long, and kept breaking down randomly for different reasons each time.

In [35]:
def sitk_N4bias(inputpath, outputpath):
    input_img = sitk.ReadImage(inputpath)
    maskImage = sitk.OtsuThreshold(input_img,0,1,200)
    inputImage = sitk.Cast(input_img,sitk.sitkFloat32)
    corrector = sitk.N4BiasFieldCorrectionImageFilter();
    output = corrector.Execute(inputImage,maskImage)
    sitk.WriteImage(output,outputpath)

Masks||OPTIONAL: PLEASE READ BELOW
Here the process of acquiring the files from each Training repository was done, and underwent pre-processing the following ways:

  • All images smoothed first, at 2 FWHM
  • All images resampled from [1,1,1] to [2,2,2]
  • All images concatenated into a 4D array
  • 4D array then cropped
  • Each file in 4D array then affixed to a padded image to standardize the size, by the axial dimension, which is the Z coordinate.
  • All non-GT scans made into a 4D array as the image pickle
  • Segmentation mask then split into 3 layers, depending on filtering what label. Here it is purely whole tumor, so all labels >0 set to 1.
  • Concatenated 4D array of GT made into mask pickle

Note: This section had to be redacted due to NDA, so instructions to replicate your own mask process is given above

Debug where we check the segmentation masks to see if they are okay. This is also to indicate that the model needs to perform 3 binary classification tasks, each on a separate area (1 only, 2 only, 4 only)

As right now the model is using semantic segmentation (only extract the ROI, not instances of ED/TC/ET individually), the labels should just be 0 (background) and 1 (tumor)

DataGenerator
Here is where experimentation with various models (2D/3D) is being done to get the desired input flow. Whether it will be 240x240 image 155 times per person, or a 240x240x155 array per person. Referring to the report will explain the datagenerator, but basically it fetches the pickled file and splits them into the masks/images to be used across one channel per scan type.

In [5]:
class SingleDataGenerator(keras.utils.Sequence):
    def __init__(self, list_IDs, batch_size=2, dim=(240,240,155), n_channels=4,
                 n_classes=3, shuffle=True):
        self.dim = dim
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.labels = labels
        self.list_IDs = list_IDs
        self.n_channels = n_channels
        self.n_classes = n_classes
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.on_epoch_end()

    def __len__(self):
        return int(np.floor(len(self.list_IDs) / self.batch_size))

    def __getitem__(self, index):
        # Generate indexes of the batch
        indexes = self.indexes[index*self.batch_size:(index+1)*self.batch_size]
        # Find list of IDs
        list_IDs_temp = [self.list_IDs[k] for k in indexes]
        # Generate data
        X, y1 = self.__data_generation(list_IDs_temp)
        return X, y1

    def on_epoch_end(self):
        self.indexes = np.arange(len(self.list_IDs))
        if self.shuffle == True:
            np.random.shuffle(self.indexes)

    def __data_generation(self, list_IDs_temp):
        # X : (n_samples, *dim, n_channels)
        # Initialization
        X = np.empty((self.batch_size, self.n_channels, *self.dim))
        y1 = np.empty((self.batch_size, 3, *self.dim))

        # Generate data
        # Decode and load the data
        for i, ID in enumerate(list_IDs_temp):
            'The labels in the provided data are: 1 for TC, 2 for ED, 4 for ET, 0 for background'
            #(TC = Tumor core, ED = edema, ET = enhancing tumor)
            '''Experimentation here'''
            X[i,] = pickle.load( open( imagelink%(ID), "rb" ) )
            y1[i,] = pickle.load( open( masklink%(ID), "rb" ) )
        return X, y1

Model
Most of these code-blocks were used from another existing source, but realistically the structure does not need to be that difficult. A U-Net is basically (and sequentially):

  • N number of Downsample blocks: 2xCNN3D and a MaxPooling
  • 1 Bottleneck: 2xCNN3D
  • N number of Upsample blocks: Upsampling Layer and 2x CNN3D. (Make sure to concatenate results)

Instance normalization is also present in each CNN block, assuming it was installed beforehand. Please make sure to install it otherwise.

In [21]:
def create_convolution_block(input_layer, n_filters, batch_normalization=False, kernel=(3, 3, 3), activation=None,
                             padding='same', strides=(1, 1, 1), instance_normalization=False):
    layer = Conv3D(n_filters, kernel, padding=padding, strides=strides)(input_layer)
    if batch_normalization:
        layer = BatchNormalization(axis=1)(layer)
    elif instance_normalization:
        try:
            from keras_contrib.layers.normalization.instancenormalization import InstanceNormalization
        except ImportError:
            raise ImportError("Install keras_contrib in order to use instance normalization."
                              "\nTry: pip install git+https://www.github.com/farizrahman4u/keras-contrib.git")
        layer = InstanceNormalization(axis=1)(layer)
    if activation is None:
        return Activation('relu')(layer)
    else:
        return activation()(layer)

def compute_level_output_shape(n_filters, depth, pool_size, image_shape):
    output_image_shape = np.asarray(np.divide(image_shape, np.power(pool_size, depth)), dtype=np.int32).tolist()
    return tuple([None, n_filters] + output_image_shape)

def get_up_convolution(n_filters, pool_size, kernel_size=(2, 2, 2), strides=(2, 2, 2), deconvolution=False):
    if deconvolution:
        return Deconvolution3D(filters=n_filters, kernel_size=kernel_size,
                               strides=strides)
    else:
        return UpSampling3D(size=pool_size)

def create_localization_module(input_layer, n_filters):
    convolution1 = create_convolution_block(input_layer, n_filters)
    convolution2 = create_convolution_block(convolution1, n_filters, kernel=(1, 1, 1))
    return convolution2

def create_up_sampling_module(input_layer, n_filters, size=(2, 2, 2)):
    up_sample = UpSampling3D(size=size)(input_layer)
    convolution = create_convolution_block(up_sample, n_filters)
    return convolution

def create_context_module(input_layer, n_level_filters, dropout_rate=0.3, data_format="channels_first"):
    convolution1 = create_convolution_block(input_layer=input_layer, n_filters=n_level_filters)
    dropout = SpatialDropout3D(rate=dropout_rate, data_format=data_format)(convolution1)
    convolution2 = create_convolution_block(input_layer=dropout, n_filters=n_level_filters)
    return convolution2

create_convolution_block = partial(create_convolution_block, activation=LeakyReLU, instance_normalization=True)

Metrics
It is important to note that for evaluating this model's performance, we cannot use conventional accuracy metrics to measure, as segmentation on a pixel by pixel basis (even getting 5-10 pixels wrong will look horrendous in accuracy), we use the dice coefficient, one of the measurable metrics of the BRATS data besides the Hausdorff distance (May use later)
The mean IOU is my take on the Jaccard Coefficient Index, but it may not be entirely correct.

In [22]:
def dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred, smooth=1.):
    y_true_f = K.flatten(y_true)
    y_pred_f = K.flatten(y_pred)
    intersection = K.sum(y_true_f * y_pred_f)
    return (2. * intersection + smooth) / (K.sum(y_true_f) + K.sum(y_pred_f) + smooth)

def dice_coefficient_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return 1-dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred)

def weighted_dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred, axis=(-3, -2, -1), smooth=0.00001):
    return K.mean(2.*(K.sum(y_true*y_pred,axis=axis)+smooth/2)/(K.sum(y_true,axis=axis)+K.sum(y_pred,axis=axis)+smooth))

def weighted_dice_coefficient_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return -weighted_dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred)

def label_wise_dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred, label_index):
    return dice_coefficient(y_true[:, label_index], y_pred[:, label_index])

def get_label_dice_coefficient_function(label_index):
    f = partial(label_wise_dice_coefficient, label_index=label_index)
    f.__setattr__('__name__', 'label_{0}_dice_coef'.format(label_index))
    return f

def mean_iou(y_true, y_pred):
        prec = []
        for t in np.arange(0.5, 1.0, 0.05):
            y_pred_ = tf.to_int32(y_pred > t)
            score, up_opt = tf.metrics.mean_iou(y_true, y_pred_, 2)
            K.get_session().run(tf.local_variables_initializer())
            with tf.control_dependencies([up_opt]):
                score = tf.identity(score)
            prec.append(score)
        return K.mean(K.stack(prec), axis=0)

dice_coef = dice_coefficient
dice_coef_loss = dice_coefficient_loss
In [26]:
'''Reference for what the UNET architecture should follow'''

Model
Creates the model here, with the 2 different block types: activation and tumortype. Survival was mentioned in the report, but was removed later due to having no relevance to the project whatsoever.

In [26]:
def down_block(x, filters, kernel_size=(3, 3, 3), padding="same", strides=1):
    c = keras.layers.Conv3D(filters, kernel_size, padding=padding, strides=strides, activation="relu")(x)
    c = keras.layers.Conv3D(filters, kernel_size, padding=padding, strides=strides, activation="relu")(c)
    p = keras.layers.MaxPool3D((2, 2, 2), (2, 2, 2))(c)
    return c, p

def up_block(x, skip, filters, kernel_size=(3, 3, 3), padding="same", strides=1):
    us = keras.layers.UpSampling3D((2, 2, 2))(x)
    concat = keras.layers.Concatenate()([us, skip])
    c = keras.layers.Conv3D(filters, kernel_size, padding=padding, strides=strides, activation="relu")(concat)
    c = keras.layers.Conv3D(filters, kernel_size, padding=padding, strides=strides, activation="relu")(c)
    return c

def bottleneck(x, filters, kernel_size=(3, 3, 3), padding="same", strides=1):
    c = keras.layers.Conv3D(filters, kernel_size, padding=padding, strides=strides, activation="relu")(x)
    c = keras.layers.Conv3D(filters, kernel_size, padding=padding, strides=strides, activation="relu")(c)
    return c
In [2]:
'''Experimental draft of the original U-Net. This is the condensed, simple to view, but less modular version'''
def UNet():
    f = [16, 32, 64, 128, 256]
    inputs = keras.layers.Input((4, 80, 96, 80))
    
    p0 = inputs
    c1, p1 = down_block(p0, f[0]) #128 -> 64
    c2, p2 = down_block(p1, f[1]) #64 -> 32
    c3, p3 = down_block(p2, f[2]) #32 -> 16
    c4, p4 = down_block(p3, f[3]) #16->8
    
    bn = bottleneck(p4, f[4])
    
    u1 = up_block(bn, c4, f[3]) #8 -> 16
    u2 = up_block(u1, c3, f[2]) #16 -> 32
    u3 = up_block(u2, c2, f[1]) #32 -> 64
    u4 = up_block(u3, c1, f[0]) #64 -> 128
    
    outputs = keras.layers.Conv2D(1, (1, 1), padding="same", activation="sigmoid")(u4)
    model = keras.models.Model(inputs, outputs)
    return model

Note that the mean_iou metric can be wonky at times, and may cause the training to have errors. Remove it if it does

NOTE:¶

The following code uses a longer, more convoluted version of the original UNET using layered "if-statements" to accomodate instance normalization, which made reorganizing very tedious. For future usage, use the above code and build around that.

          'batch_size': 2,
          'n_classes': 3,
          'n_channels': 4,

training_generator = SingleDataGenerator(partition['train'], **params)
validation_generator = SingleDataGenerator(partition['test'], **params)

                                   mode='auto')

                                     save_weights_only=False, mode='auto', period=1)
'epoch originally 100'

                              epochs=20, nb_worker=4,
                   callbacks=[cb_1,cb_2])

In [31]:
history_1_pred = results.history
pickle.dump( history_1_pred, open( "./weights/history_1_pred.pkl", "wb" ) )

It is important to note that accuracy/loss is not a good factor to measure peformance in this case, as segmentation focuses on a different aspect and does not need to include true-negative cases like regular classification models. Thus, only the dice coefficient will be used as the performance metric.

Load the Model
Whilst it may be a bad idea to put this section so far down, if you wish to skip the training above, simply load the model and weights I provided in the folder. Keep in mind the last time these weights were made was quite awhile ago, so it may not be properly trained.
Also remember that if you load this now, THEN compile, the entire weights will be wiped, meaning you have to train from the beginning. Order matters!!

In [99]:

Testing the model
Testing the trained model on the validation data. Keep in mind: If the majority of the array pixels are not some value with e-04, the model did not train properly, you will need to rerun it again

params = {'dim': (80,96,80),
          'batch_size': 2,
          'n_classes': 3,
          'n_channels': 4,
          'shuffle': False}

# Turned shuffle off so that we can match the values in the dictionary to the predictions. 
# This way we can compare the predictions side-by-side with the ground truth.
validation_generator = SingleDataGenerator(partition['holdout'], **params)

predictions = model1.predict_generator(generator=validation_generator)
# print('Test loss:', score[0])
# print('Test accuracy:', score[1])
print(predictions)
pickle.dump( predictions, open( "./weights/predictions.pkl", "wb" ) )

Testing¶

To determine the output's validity, we plot the original mask (left) compared to the deep learning tested version (right) and see how does its outline accuracy hold up:

In [113]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
# ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
# imlist = [im0[40],im1[40],im2[40],im3[40],impred0[40]]
imlist = [im0[48],impred0[48], im0[50], impred0[50]]
j = 0
for i in range(1, 5):
    plt.subplot(2, 4, i)
    plt.imshow(imlist[j], cmap='bone')
    j += 1

A more in-depth version is below, where across several scan-types, the model is not able to accurately catch the tiny outlines inbetween tumors. This is considered an "edge case", or one-off mistake, as seen in the first 4 scans, only the 1st and 4th accurately show the outlines. 2 and 4 show them mixed together, which is what the model assumes as "better safe than sorry" and includes them.

End of Whole Tumor Section¶

The final result is the predicted (1st row) against the Ground Truth (2nd row), which shows the predicted has minor issues dealing with small pixels, and overgeneralizes due to the downsampling of the original image.

(The GT was from a 240,240,155 originally, with the predicted from a 86,90,80. With pixels this small, alot of details would disappear). Nonetheless, with a competitive dice score of 0.833~0.85 (NVIDIA and Imperial Winners around 0.87~0.91 respectively), this model can be considered a success

Given that all mandatory components have been completed in segmenting the overall ROI of the tumor, the next steps are to:

  • Perform Instance segmentation, the next level where instead of just the ROI, it is now all 3 layer types

  • Classify the ROI (semantic or instance, doesn't really matter) into HGG or LGG. This is technically the main point of the entire model, it being a Tumour Grading Model
    • However, one of the main issues present is that there is no clear indication of Grades 1-4, which means classifying them into multiclasses does not work. The only alternative is to classify them binary-wise (HGG/LGG), or to use a more extreme method: to determine their life expectancy given the tumor.

    In this section, the BRATS 2018 challenge came with an additional piece of data: the patient's survival rate. This .csv file contains the patient's age, survival rate in days (according to the official website) and Resection Status, which contains the state whether they have undergone GTR (Gross Total Resection. Basically post-operation).

    In the official challenge, only patients with GTR were to be evaluated. But for this dissertation, due to time constraints, it may be ignored entirely. (Ideally this is to indicate whether the tumor was successfully removed, as post-GTR, survival rate should almost always increase. If it doesn't, it means some still remained)


    Note: These are all optional and purely for analysis. Skip to the next red header to actually progress

    In [63]:
    import random as r
import skimage.io as io
#function to read one subject data
def create_data_onesubject_val(src, mask,count, label=False):
    files = glob.glob(src + mask, recursive=True)
    r.seed(9)
    r.shuffle(files)    # shuffle patients
    k = len(files) - count -1
    imgs = []
    file = files[k]
    print('Processing---', mask,'--',file)
    
    img = io.imread(file, plugin='simpleitk')
    #img = trans.resize(img, resize, mode='constant')
    if label:
        if label_num == 5:
            img[img != 0] = 1       #Region 1 => 1+2+3+4 complete tumor
        if label_num == 1:
            img[img != 1] = 0       #only left necrosis
        if label_num == 2:
            img[img == 2] = 0       #turn edema to 0
            img[img != 0] = 1       #only keep necrosis, ET, NET = Tumor core
        if label_num == 4:
            img[img != 4] = 0       #only left ET
            img[img == 4] = 1
        img = img.astype('float32')
    else:
        img = (img-img.mean()) / img.std()      #normalization => zero mean   !!!care for the std=0 problem
        img = img.astype('float32')
    for slice in range(155):     #choose the slice range
        img_t = img[slice,:,:]
        img_t =img_t.reshape((1,)+img_t.shape)
        img_t =img_t.reshape((1,)+img_t.shape)   #become rank 4
        #img_g = augmentation(img_t,num_of_aug)
        for n in range(img_t.shape[0]):
            imgs.append(img_t[n,:,:,:])
    
    return np.array(imgs)

    Since the masks need to be slightly more advanced, reference to the UCL/Imperial winners was done to acquire some insight as to WHAT exactly from these labels compose the 3 layers. The following information was gathered: out of the labels [0,1,2,4]:

  • Tumor core = [0,1,0,1]
  • Whole Tumor = [0,1,1,1]
  • Enhancing Tumor = [0,0,0,1]

    In [17]:
    class DataGenerator(keras.utils.Sequence):
    def __init__(self, list_IDs, batch_size=2, dim=(240,240,155), n_channels=4,
                 n_classes=4, shuffle=True):
        self.dim = dim
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.labels = labels
        self.list_IDs = list_IDs
        self.n_channels = n_channels
        self.n_classes = n_classes
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.on_epoch_end()

    def __len__(self):
        return int(np.floor(len(self.list_IDs) / self.batch_size))

    def __getitem__(self, index):
        # Generate indexes of the batch
        indexes = self.indexes[index*self.batch_size:(index+1)*self.batch_size]
        # Find list of IDs
        list_IDs_temp = [self.list_IDs[k] for k in indexes]
        # Generate data
        X, y1 = self.__data_generation(list_IDs_temp)
        return X, y1

    def on_epoch_end(self):
        self.indexes = np.arange(len(self.list_IDs))
        if self.shuffle == True:
            np.random.shuffle(self.indexes)

    def __data_generation(self, list_IDs_temp):
        # X : (n_samples, *dim, n_channels)
        # Initialization
        X = np.empty((self.batch_size, self.n_channels, *self.dim))
        y1 = np.empty((self.batch_size, 3, *self.dim))

        # Generate data
        # Decode and load the data
        for i, ID in enumerate(list_IDs_temp):
            'The labels in the provided data are: 1 for TC, 2 for ED, 4 for ET, 0 for background'
            #(TC = Tumor core, ED = edema, ET = enhancing tumor)
            '''Experimentation here'''
            X[i,] = pickle.load( open( oldimagelink%(ID), "rb" ) )
            y1[i,] = pickle.load( open( oldmasklink%(ID), "rb" ) )
            #y1[i,] = pickle.load( open( testmasklink%(ID), "rb" ) )
        '''This section is currently commented out, but will be included once the focus moves from 
        ROI extraction to tumor layer extraction. As of right now, it is a one-off binary case.'''
        #return X, keras.utils.to_categorical(y1, num_classes=self.n_classes)
        return X, y1

    params = {'dim': (88,105,88),
          'batch_size': 2,
          #originally n_classes=3
          'n_classes': 4,
          'n_channels': 4,
          'shuffle': True}

# Generators

validation_generator = DataGenerator(partition['test'], **params)

cb_1=keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', min_delta=0, patience=2, verbose=0, 
                                   mode='auto')
cb_2=keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath="./weights/2pred_weights.{epoch:02d}-{val_loss:.2f}.hdf5", 
                                     monitor='val_loss', verbose=0, save_best_only=True, 
                                     save_weights_only=False, mode='auto', period=1)


results = model2.fit_generator(generator=training_generator, 
                              validation_data=validation_generator,
                              epochs=20, 
                              nb_worker=4,
                              callbacks=[cb_1,cb_2])
model2.save("./model/model_2.hdf5")

    plt.style.use("ggplot")
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))
titlemetric = ['Weighted Dice Coefficient', 'Loss']

for i in range(1,3):
    fig.add_subplot(1,2,i)
    plt.title(titlemetric[i-1])
    if(i-1==0):
        plt.plot(history_2_pred['val_weighted_dice_coefficient'], label='validation weighted dice')
        plt.plot(history_2_pred['weighted_dice_coefficient'], label = 'weighted training dice')
    else:
        plt.plot(history_2_pred['val_loss'], label='validation')
        plt.plot(history_2_pred['loss'], label = 'training')
    plt.xlabel("Epoch #")
    plt.ylabel("Dice Score")
    plt.legend(loc="lower left")

    Success!!¶

    We have successfully extracted ALL layers of the tumor, from TC down to WT!! Based off the above comparison, the differences are minor due to downsampling, but otherwise, the model performs BEAUTIFULLY at a whopping 0.88 dice score. Additional work could be done, where further improvement on the core layer in specific could be done

    This means the segmentation section is entirely complete, where we now write the segmentations into files for later usage/reference!! Now the only thing remaining is the 2nd-half of the architecture: classifying (grading) these now extracted tumors!

    In [88]:
    class classDataGenerator(keras.utils.Sequence):
    'Generates data for Keras'
    def __init__(self, list_IDs, batch_size=2, dim=(240,240,155), n_channels=4,
                 n_classes=3, shuffle=True):
        'Initialization'
        self.dim = dim
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.labels = labels
        self.list_IDs = list_IDs
        self.n_channels = n_channels
        self.n_classes = n_classes
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.on_epoch_end()

    def __len__(self):
        'Denotes the number of batches per epoch'
        return int(np.floor(len(self.list_IDs) / self.batch_size))

    def __getitem__(self, index):
        'Generate one batch of data'
        # Generate indexes of the batch
        indexes = self.indexes[index*self.batch_size:(index+1)*self.batch_size]

        # Find list of IDs
        list_IDs_temp = [self.list_IDs[k] for k in indexes]

        # Generate data
        X, y1, y2 = self.__data_generation(list_IDs_temp)

        return X, [y1, y2]

    def on_epoch_end(self):
        'Updates indexes after each epoch'
        self.indexes = np.arange(len(self.list_IDs))
        if self.shuffle == True:
            np.random.shuffle(self.indexes)

    def __data_generation(self, list_IDs_temp):
        'Generates data containing batch_size samples' # X : (n_samples, *dim, n_channels)
        # Initialization
        X = np.empty((self.batch_size, self.n_channels, *self.dim))
        y1 = np.empty((self.batch_size, 3, *self.dim))
        y2 = np.empty(self.batch_size)
#         y2 = list()

        # Generate data
        # Decode and load the data
        for i, ID in enumerate(list_IDs_temp):

            # 1) the "enhancing tumor" (ET), 2) the "tumor core" (TC), and 3) the "whole tumor" (WT) 
            # The ET is described by areas that show hyper-intensity in T1Gd when compared to T1, but also when compared to healthy white matter in T1Gd. The TC describes the bulk of the tumor, which is what is typically resected. The TC entails the ET, as well as the necrotic (fluid-filled) and the non-enhancing (solid) parts of the tumor. The appearance of the necrotic (NCR) and the non-enhancing (NET) tumor core is typically hypo-intense in T1-Gd when compared to T1. The WT describes the complete extent of the disease, as it entails the TC and the peritumoral edema (ED), which is typically depicted by hyper-intense signal in FLAIR.
            # The labels in the provided data are: 
            # 1 for NCR & NET (necrotic (NCR) and the non-enhancing (NET) tumor core) = TC ("tumor core")
            # 2 for ED ("peritumoral edema")
            # 4 for ET ("enhancing tumor")
            # 0 for everything else

            X[i,] = pickle.load( open( oldimagelink%(ID), "rb" ) )
            y1[i,] = pickle.load( open( oldmasklink%(ID), "rb" ) )
            y2[i,] = tumor_type_dict[ID]
            
#         return X, keras.utils.to_categorical(y, num_classes=self.n_classes)
        return X, y1, y2

cb_1=keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', min_delta=0, patience=2, verbose=0, mode='auto')
cb_2=keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath="./weights/2pred_weights.{epoch:02d}-{val_loss:.2f}.hdf5", monitor='val_loss', verbose=0, save_best_only=True, save_weights_only=False, mode='auto', period=1)

                    validation_data=validation_generator,
                   epochs=20, 
                   nb_worker=4,
                   callbacks=[cb_1,cb_2])
model.save('./model/model_4.hdf5')

Brats18_CBICA_AQV_1 : [0.]
0

    Whilst this is not a clear indicator of the tumor classifier's success, it does have ~68% accuracy, primarily due to multiple things:

  • Data imbalance. 210 HGG to 75 LGG makes the model almost always just assume HGG

  • Label imbalance. Most of the data in here are synthetic data, which upon analysis has only 2 classtypes (enhancing and edema, instead of core(enhancing+necro) and edema. Since core is pivotal to indicating HGG, the model instantly assumes LGG, which is what they normally look like.

  • Model. Due to lack of time, a basic CNN model was made to rush classification. If further time was spent on tuning hyperparameters or increasing the pixel size, accuracy might have improved
    • Still, the model performed as asked, and is now capable of extracting the tumor layer-by-layer, and diagnosing the severity.

    With all of that done, the model is not cohesively a full tool, but it was able to perform the tasks required in the end, which is all the code presented does.
